{"award_age":54.0,"bio_image":"full\/2c41ce8e3c5f7f40a1ac19bce184ea17d95ba945.jpg","category":"Peace","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1944-10-15T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/9\/9b\/David_Trimble.jpg\/220px-David_Trimble.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble","mini_bio":"<p><b>William David Trimble, Baron Trimble<\/b>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Her_Majesty%27s_Most_Honourable_Privy_Council\" title=\"Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council\" class=\"mw-redirect\">PC<\/a> (born 15 October 1944), is a British politician who was the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/First_Minister_of_Northern_Ireland\" title=\"First Minister of Northern Ireland\" class=\"mw-redirect\">First Minister of Northern Ireland<\/a> from 1998 to 2002, and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ulster_Unionist_Party\" title=\"Ulster Unionist Party\">Leader of the Ulster Unionist Party<\/a> from 1995 to 2005.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica1_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-britannica1-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was also the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)\" title=\"Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Member of Parliament<\/a> for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Upper_Bann_(UK_Parliament_constituency)\" title=\"Upper Bann (UK Parliament constituency)\">Upper Bann<\/a> from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Upper_Bann_by-election,_1990\" title=\"Upper Bann by-election, 1990\">1990<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/UK_general_election,_2005\" title=\"UK general election, 2005\" class=\"mw-redirect\">2005<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Member_of_the_Legislative_Assembly_(Northern_Ireland)\" title=\"Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)\">Member of the Legislative Assembly<\/a> (MLA) for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Upper_Bann_(Assembly_constituency)\" title=\"Upper Bann (Assembly constituency)\">Upper Bann<\/a> from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Good_Friday_Agreement\" title=\"Good Friday Agreement\">1998<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Northern_Ireland_Assembly_election,_2007\" title=\"Northern Ireland Assembly election, 2007\">2007<\/a>. In 2006, he was made a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Life_peer\" title=\"Life peer\">life peer<\/a> in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/House_of_Lords\" title=\"House of Lords\">House of Lords<\/a> and a year later left the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ulster_Unionist_Party\" title=\"Ulster Unionist Party\">UUP<\/a> to join the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Conservative_Party_(UK)\" title=\"Conservative Party (UK)\">Conservative Party<\/a>.<\/p><p>Lord Trimble began his career as a Professor of Law at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Queen%27s_University_of_Belfast\" title=\"The Queen's University of Belfast\" class=\"mw-redirect\">The Queen's University of Belfast<\/a> in the 1970s, during which time he began to get involved with the paramilitary-linked <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vanguard_Progressive_Unionist_Party\" title=\"Vanguard Progressive Unionist Party\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Vanguard Progressive Unionist Party<\/a>. He was elected to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Northern_Ireland_Constitutional_Convention\" title=\"Northern Ireland Constitutional Convention\">Northern Ireland Constitutional Convention<\/a> in 1975, and joined the UUP in 1978 after the VPUP disbanded.<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica1_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-britannica1-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Remaining at Queen's University, he continued his academic career until being elected as the MP for Upper Bann in 1990. In 1995 he was unexpectedly elected as the Leader of the UUP.<sup id=\"cite_ref-britannica1_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-britannica1-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was instrumental in the negotiations that led to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Good_Friday_Agreement\" title=\"Good Friday Agreement\">Good Friday Agreement<\/a> in 1998, and (along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Hume\" title=\"John Hume\">John Hume<\/a>) won the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> that year for his efforts. He was later elected to become the first First Minister of Northern Ireland, although his tenure was turbulent and frequently interrupted by disagreements over the extent of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Provisional_Irish_Republican_Army\" title=\"Provisional Irish Republican Army\">Provisional Irish Republican Army<\/a> decommissioning.<\/p><p>After being defeated at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/UK_general_election,_2005\" title=\"UK general election, 2005\" class=\"mw-redirect\">2005 general election<\/a>, Trimble resigned the leadership of the UUP soon afterwards. In June 2006, he accepted a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Life_peer\" title=\"Life peer\">life peerage<\/a> in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/British_House_of_Lords\" title=\"British House of Lords\" class=\"mw-redirect\">House of Lords<\/a>, taking the title of <i>Baron Trimble, of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lisnagarvey\" title=\"Lisnagarvey\">Lisnagarvey<\/a> in the County of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/County_Antrim\" title=\"County Antrim\">Antrim<\/a><\/i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gazette_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-Gazette-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He did not stand again for the Assembly, which finally reconvened in 2007, instead leaving the UUP to join the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Conservative_Party_(UK)\" title=\"Conservative Party (UK)\">Conservative Party<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-conservatives_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/David_Trimble#cite_note-conservatives-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"David Trimble","place_of_birth":"Bangor ,  County Down , Northern Ireland","place_of_death":null,"text":"David Trimble , Peace, 1998","year":1998.0}